id: claude-slash-command
title: Claude Code /tnl-feature skill installation
scope: feature
owners: [@jana]
paths: [src/commands/init.ts]
surfaces: [tnl init]
dependencies: [cli-init]

intent:
  When `tnl init` runs against a project where Claude Code is a target
  agent, it writes the `/tnl-feature` slash command to
  `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` in addition to the CLAUDE.md
  stanza. The skill packages the TNL workflow (scope → clarify →
  propose → wait → implement → self-attest) as a single
  user-invocable command. The CLAUDE.md stanza references the skill
  by name so agents and users discover it.

behaviors:
  - `src/commands/init.ts` MUST contain a fixed string constant `TNL_FEATURE_SKILL_TEMPLATE` whose body is the markdown content for `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md`. The content MUST be a thin pointer that (a) has YAML frontmatter with `description:`, (b) references `$ARGUMENTS`, (c) tells the agent to follow the TNL task flow defined in `CLAUDE.md` (the "TNL — Typed Natural Language" section) as authoritative, (d) does NOT duplicate the numbered task-flow steps. Single source of truth is the CLAUDE.md stanza; duplicating steps across stanza and skill creates drift and causes session-to-session variance depending on whether `/tnl-feature` was invoked.
  - When `tnl init` determines Claude is a target agent (either `.claude/` is present or `--agent claude` was passed), init MUST write `<cwd>/.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` with `TNL_FEATURE_SKILL_TEMPLATE` content. It MUST create `.claude/commands/` if absent.
  - If `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` already exists, init MUST leave the file untouched and report the skip.
  - This installation step MAY be suppressed by `tnl init`'s `--no-skill` or `--minimal` opt-out flag (defined in `cli-init.tnl`). When suppressed, the step is skipped and the summary reports `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` under `Skipped (opt-out)` rather than `Created` or `Skipped (already present)`.
  - The skill write MUST happen only for Claude targets. When the only target is `codex` or `gemini`, init MUST NOT create `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md`.
  - The CLAUDE.md stanza appended by init MUST reference the `/tnl-feature` command by name when Claude is a target. Other agents' stanzas MUST NOT reference it. The stanza differentiation MAY be done via separate templates or a conditional addition to the base stanza.
  - The end-of-run summary MUST include `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` in the `Created` or `Skipped (already present)` section when Claude is a target.
  - Tests MUST cover: `.claude/commands/tnl-feature.md` written when `--agent claude` is passed and the file is absent; `.claude/commands/` directory auto-created; existing skill file → skipped and reported; skill NOT written when `--agent codex` or `--agent gemini`; Claude stanza contains `/tnl-feature`; non-Claude stanzas do NOT contain `/tnl-feature`; end-of-run summary includes the skill path on first run; `TNL_FEATURE_SKILL_TEMPLATE` contains frontmatter `description:`, `$ARGUMENTS`, and a reference to `CLAUDE.md`; `TNL_FEATURE_SKILL_TEMPLATE` does NOT contain `## 3.` / `## 5.` / `## 7.` numbered-step markers that would duplicate the stanza flow.

non-goals:
  - Iterating on the `/tnl-feature` step text beyond the initial template — content tweaks over time are edits to this TNL, not new TNLs.
  - Installing or configuring the PreToolUse hook — next A6 TNL.
  - Packaging a Claude Code plugin — deferred to B4.
  - Publishing the skill to a registry or marketplace.
  - Skills for other agents (Codex, Gemini) — those surfaces don't expose slash commands in v1 scope.

rationale:
  Why embed the skill template as a string constant rather than bundle
  a separate template file: matches the existing `WORKFLOW_TEMPLATE`
  pattern in the same module. When the template count outgrows
  inline constants, we switch to a bundled `templates/` directory.

  Why tie skill installation to the Claude target only: agents without
  slash-command surfaces can't use the file. Installing it for them
  would be dead weight.

  Why CLAUDE.md must reference the skill: the skill is user-invoked
  via `/tnl-feature`. Without a pointer in CLAUDE.md, agents and
  users won't discover it.
